  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Ninth Day
  author: Kim Heun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At sorrow's end, I cannot help but turn to chrysanthemum branches—
    three times I breathe their pure fragrance to substitute for wine.
    A wanderer meeting the festive season cannot bear its weight,
    and leaning on the heights, I realize how distant I have become.

    Scattered grasses and trees exhaust the late autumn's end,
    while misty waves grow thin as daylight fades away.
    Far, so far when I climb the mountain to gaze toward my homeland—
    only then do I know what drunken verses I have lost.

    I venture to the mountain's peak and find it is Double Ninth,
    and hastily purchase cloudy wine from the village below.
    The festive season strikes the lonely heart of this traveler with wonder,
    and cold flowers hold only the fragrance of my distant home.

    Where shall I meet this evening when another year arrives?
    Today my small boat remains stranded in this foreign land.
    Unable to see Chang'an, I feel myself grow old,
    while solitary clouds and setting sun merge into obscurity.
  footnotes:
    - Double Ninth (中陽) refers to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month, a traditional East Asian festival celebrated on high places.
    - Chang'an (長安) refers to the ancient capital, symbolizing home and a place of belonging.
